# Gameplay Architecture

- Separate input, domain logic, and presentation.
- Input must emit commands; commands drive gameplay state changes.
- Keep gameplay rules in plain C# services where possible, not MonoBehaviours.
- Use events for cross-system communication; avoid deep direct references.
- Prefer state machines for boss/player combat states.

# Timing Rules

- Deterministic gameplay decisions happen in fixed-step updates.
- Visual-only interpolation and effects happen in frame updates.

# Example

```csharp
// BAD: input directly mutates combat state in view script
if (Input.GetKeyDown(KeyCode.Space)) _boss.Stun();

// GOOD: input -> command -> domain handler
if (_input.ParryPressed) _commandBus.Publish(new ParryCommand(playerId));
```
